      <h2>Medicare Rebates & Tax Deductions</h2>

      <h3>Medicare Benefits Schedule (MBS) Rebates</h3>

      <p>Medicare provides rebates for gastric band surgery if you meet medical criteria:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>MBS Item 31569 (Gastric band placement):</strong> $743.40 rebate</li>
        <li><strong>MBS Item 31585 (Gastric band removal):</strong> ~$235 rebate</li>
        <li><strong>MBS Item 20791 (Anaesthetist):</strong> ~$300 rebate</li>
        <li><strong>Total initial surgery rebate:</strong> ~$1,043</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Medical Eligibility Criteria</h3>

      <p>To qualify for Medicare rebates, you must meet ONE of these criteria:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>BMI ≥40</strong> (any circumstances)</li>
        <li><strong>BMI ≥35</strong> with obesity-related conditions:
          <ul>
            <li>Type 2 diabetes</li>
            <li>Cardiovascular disease</li>
            <li>Obstructive sleep apnea</li>
            <li>Severe joint disease</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Tax Deductions for Medical Expenses</h3>

      <p>Gastric band surgery is tax deductible if it's medically necessary:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Net Medical Expenses Tax Offset:</strong> Claim out-of-pocket expenses above <strong>$2,759</strong> (2024-25)</li>
        <li><strong>What you can claim:</strong> Surgeon/anaesthetist gap fees, hospital excess, pre-surgery consultations, band adjustments, follow-up appointments, vitamins (if prescribed)</li>
        <li><strong>What you can't claim:</strong> Costs covered by insurance, Medicare rebates, gym memberships</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Why Gastric Band Demand Has Collapsed in Australia</h2>

      <p>Gastric band procedures have declined by <strong>85% since 2011</strong> in Australia. Here's why:</p>

      <h3>Poor Long-Term Weight Loss Results</h3>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Gastric band:</strong> 40-50% excess weight loss</li>
        <li><strong>Gastric sleeve:</strong> 60-65% excess weight loss</li>
        <li><strong>Gastric bypass:</strong> 65-75% excess weight loss</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>High Complication & Removal Rates</h3>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>40-60% of patients</strong> require band removal within 10 years</li>
        <li><strong>15-20%</strong> experience band slippage</li>
        <li><strong>1-3%</strong> experience band erosion (requires emergency surgery)</li>
        <li><strong>10-15%</strong> have port complications</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Lifestyle Restrictions & Quality of Life</h3>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Frequent vomiting</strong> if food not chewed properly</li>
        <li><strong>Severe food restrictions</strong> (bread, pasta, rice often not tolerated)</li>
        <li><strong>Constant adjustments</strong> required throughout life</li>
        <li><strong>High maintenance</strong> compared to sleeve/bypass</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Superior Alternatives Now Available</h3>

      <p>Gastric sleeve surgery has become the gold standard in Australia because it offers:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Better weight loss:</strong> 60-65% vs 40-50% excess weight loss</li>
        <li><strong>One-time procedure:</strong> No adjustments needed</li>
        <li><strong>Lower complication rates:</strong> More predictable outcomes</li>
        <li><strong>Better quality of life:</strong> Fewer food intolerances</li>
        <li><strong>Similar cost upfront:</strong> Only $500-$1,000 more than band</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="danger-box">
        <strong>Most Surgeons No Longer Recommend Gastric Band</strong>
        <p>Due to poor outcomes, most Australian bariatric surgeons now reserve gastric band for rare cases only (e.g., patients who refuse permanent procedures, very high surgical risk). If your surgeon recommends gastric band as your first option, consider seeking a second opinion to discuss gastric sleeve or bypass alternatives.</p>
